# 2026-06-16 — Immich Self-Hosted Photo Backup (Docker Compose)

## Objective
Deploy Immich (self-hosted Google Photos alternative) on the always-on
homelab for automatic phone photo/video backup with AI face/object
recognition, exposed for backup from anywhere.

## Why Ubuntu Server (not Nobara)
- Immich needs to be **always on** for phone auto-backup to work whenever a
  photo is taken — so it belongs on the always-on homelab, not the Nobara
  workstation (which gets turned off).

## What Was Accomplished

### Deployment (Docker Compose)
- Created ~/immich and pulled Immich's official docker-compose.yml and
  example.env (-> .env).
- Edited .env:
  - UPLOAD_LOCATION set to a folder on the DataHDD (the roomy 1TB spinning
    disk with ~200GB free), NOT the NVMe system disk — bulk photo storage
    belongs on the big disk, and keeps the system disk safe from filling.
  - DB_PASSWORD changed off the default.
- Brought the stack up with `docker compose up -d`. Four containers:
  immich-server, immich-machine-learning (the large AI image), postgres,
  redis. Confirmed all healthy (server briefly showed unhealthy during
  first-run DB migrations, then went healthy — normal).
- Created the admin account in the web UI (first account = admin).

### Remote Access (Cloudflare Tunnel)
- Added a public hostname on the existing tunnel pointing to the Docker
  bridge gateway address — same pattern as n8n,
  because cloudflared is a bridged container and can't reach host-published
  ports via localhost.
- Confirmed Immich loads at its public hostname.

### Phone App
- Installed the Immich app on iPhone, connected to the server via the public
  hostname, logged in, and set up backup.
- Note: back up the main "Recents"/"All Photos" album (the full library) so
  saved images — not just camera photos — are captured. iOS smart albums
  like "Recently Saved" are just filtered views of the same library.

## Storage Notes
- Library lives on the DataHDD (~200GB free now). Can grow the disk later
  from ~557GB of free physical space (expand-in-place: resize in Proxmox
  -> growpart + resize2fs), never migrate.
- HDD speed is fine for a photo gallery — no need for NVMe here.

## What I Learned
- Immich is a multi-container Docker Compose app (server + ML + postgres +
  redis); the machine-learning image is the largest and slowest to pull
- The server container reports "unhealthy" briefly on first start while it
  runs DB migrations — normal, resolves on its own
- Bulk-data services (photos, media) belong on the large HDD, not the system
  NVMe, to avoid filling the root filesystem
- The Docker bridge gateway is the reliable tunnel origin for
  any bridged-container setup — reused from the n8n fix
- This was also good hands-on Docker Compose practice ahead of the planned
  full-stack Compose migration

